<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38063c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38063c">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38063c"> 63(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> cyclorama </blockquote> <dd class="well"><mm class="note">Note: In the theatre this is a backcloth or curved wall at the back of the stage, usually for representations of the sky. See <i>The Times</i>, issue of 2 May 1930- 12/5: <b>Stage Lighting and the <mark>Cyclorama</mark> / Demonstration Model at Science Museum</b> An unusually instructive theatre model has been built by the workshops of the Science Museum, South Kensington, to demonstrate the most recent practice in stage lighting. It consists of a miniature stage, supporting model actors and a symbolic set designed by Miss Doria Paston, and backed by a plain silvered cyclorama (used as the sky or back piece of the stage), which will take and reflect any colour or combination of colours shone upon it from a small battery of lights arranged in the three primary colours.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> It is believed that the Cambridge Festival Theatre is the only place of entertainment in this country which has so far employed this device. </mm> </dd></dl>
